<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 19 日星期三 08:01:46 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[What’s the Matter With Barbie?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>格蕾塔·葛韦格饰演的<em>芭比娃娃</em>是一部迷人的大片冒险片，讲述了作为一个女人在社会中生存的磨难。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/8SaJ0mFhtOLswlesxFB3W53cibs=/0x0:3732x2099/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rev_1_BAR_TT2_006_High_Res_JPEG_1/original.jpg" alt="《芭比娃娃》中的芭比和肯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟</figcaption></figure>芭比乐园是一个乌托邦式的粉色天堂，里面有每一个芭比娃娃的真人大小版本，这里的生活是一场漫长的派对。芭比娃娃（玛格特·罗比饰演）每天早上在她梦想中的房子里醒来，整天和其他芭比娃娃以及许多仰慕的肯斯一起在海滩上玩耍，然后举办一个女孩之夜，这是一个精心设计的长舞蹈序列。这是一种充满欢乐的生活，是一个由品牌管理的世界，不允许任何事情出错，芭比完美的拱形高跟鞋也不允许接触地板。这就是当她在跳舞时大声问“你们想过死吗？”时特别有趣的地方。记录划痕。<br><br>格蕾塔·葛韦格 (Greta Gerwig) 饰演的<em>芭比娃娃</em>的行动就此开始，这是一场轰动一时的冒险，她烘烤了一个美泰品牌的大蛋糕，并试图把它吃掉，嘲笑美国最著名的娃娃的政治局限性，同时也给她带来了一段可信的英雄之旅。将元幽默与大量激励性真诚相结合并不是一件容易的事，但<em>芭比娃娃</em>是一个非常迷人的成功，对于一个塑料偶像来说，这是一次自我完善的冒险之旅，其存在的理由是永远不会改变，永远是同样完美的理想。与葛韦格的前两部电影一样——大获成功的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-review/544721/"><em>《伯德小姐</em></a>》和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/little-women-review-saiorse-ronan-florence-pugh/604114/"><em>《小妇人》</em></a> ——这部电影巧妙地思考了一个噩梦般的难题：仅仅试图以女性的身份存在于社会中，只是穿着更多的日光服装。<br><br>最初，<em>芭比娃娃</em>似乎会遵循其他有关品牌的电影设定的公式，例如<em>《乐高大电影》</em>和<em>《刺猬索尼克》</em> ，其中来自品牌世界的角色跨越某些维度障碍进入我们的世界，犯错误，并试图计算与令人沮丧的现实世俗。罗比的芭比娃娃（她的全名是刻板芭比娃娃，以区别于从事医生或总统等工作的芭比娃娃）被迫通过一系列戏剧性事件与她的存在焦虑作斗争，她的任务是探寻现实世界弄清楚她出了什么问题。<br><br>芭比最喜欢的肯（瑞恩·高斯林饰）尾随其后，部分是为了支持，部分是因为他生活中唯一的作用就是靠近她。虽然芭比是《芭比乐园》围绕的对象，但肯显然缺乏目标，反复强调他的工作被简单地指定为“海滩”——不是救生员，甚至不是游泳运动员。他只是海滩肯，永远穿着短裤站在沙滩上，脸上挂着笑容。高斯林的表演滑稽地揭示了这个漫无目的的动作人物浅薄但强烈的痛苦，这是一种有血有肉的<em>玩具</em>总动员心理剧（尽管芭比确实明确表示，她和她所有的朋友在他们的生殖器处只有毫无特征的肿块）。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">阅读：芭比真的能拥有这一切吗？</a><br><br>如果您对芭比乐园的规则以及它如何与我们的现实共存有任何疑问，请放弃。葛韦格与她的搭档兼经常合作者诺亚·鲍姆巴赫 (Noah Baumbach) 共同创作了这部电影，她并不太在意宇宙间的运输规则——只要知道芭比和肯在不同环境之间轻松跳跃是可行的。更重要的是，面对我们的世界，芭比必须面对双重恐惧：认识到女性的生活并不是美泰产品所宣传的修剪整齐、无所不能的梦想，而且现实世界中的许多女性事实上，她怨恨她代表了一个不可能的标准。<br><br>这种自我指涉的策略很容易落空：自 1959 年推出以来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">芭比娃娃作为女权主义象征的局限性</a>就一直受到广泛讨论。美泰对这部电影的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/07/10/after-barbie-mattel-is-raiding-its-entire-toybox">深入参与</a>也似乎是一个创意陷阱，“对于葛韦格来说，无论她多么努力地向观众眨眼，她都很难克服这一点。但是，通过将芭比娃娃放在我们阴郁的星球上并迫使她考虑自己的目的，葛韦格确实以某种方式挖掘出了一些真正的深度。把刻板的芭比从芭比乐园中移走，然后把她扔到洛杉矶，她只是另一个在这个对她的存在本质上充满敌意的世界中努力寻找意义的女人。她现实生活中的化身是格洛丽亚（亚莉卡·费雷拉饰演的可爱角色），一位美泰公司的员工，对 21 世纪的女性气质也充满了类似的怀疑。<br><br>与此同时，肯遇到了一个肯定和支持他的世界（或者至少是他所占据的强壮的男性身体），这让他充满了放射性的赋权感。这就是<em>芭比</em>的元智慧实际上与真实情节的交叉点：葛韦格聪明地意识到，现实生活中的芭比只会面临怀疑和批评，而肯则是一个终极空容器，等待着被废话填满。但<em>芭比</em>从来没有陷入一场廉价的男女生最终对决；它只是考虑了向我们这些疲惫而自愿的消费者出售自我形象的不同方式，即使世界变得更加精明和愤世嫉俗。它通过明亮的音乐数字、尖刻的俏皮话和正确的感伤主义来做到这一点，更令人印象深刻。<em>芭比</em>知道，但它的眼中仍然闪烁着乐观的光芒，担心主角可能会超越其他人对她的预测。毕竟，没有什么危机是一场好的舞会解决不了的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 23:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/</item><item><title><![CDATA[How Hollywood’s Businessmen Got It So Wrong]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与 Xochitl Gonzalez 对话，了解谁真正打破了娱乐业<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/q7mt7K_3OOEUUjvqB4N6Z2-EQZM=/1x313:6041x3710/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1540946623-1/original.jpg" alt="作家的罢工纠察队标语列出要求与流媒体收入" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>罗宾·贝克/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>上周，SAG-AFTRA 约 16 万名成员参加了罢工，加入了自 5 月份以来一直在罢工的美国作家协会。正如我的同事 Xochitl Gonzalez <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">所说</a>，“好莱坞机器……已经正式停止运转。”我和 Xochitl 聊了聊谁真正打破了好莱坞。<br><br>首先，这是来自<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/">田纳西州是民主国家吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/">唐纳德·特朗普的“可怕消息”</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastructure/674735/">赞扬电话号码</a></li><strong>最高管理层的无知</strong><br><br>昨天，我的同事索奇特尔·冈萨雷斯（Xochitl Gonzalez）（她本人也是一名罢工编剧）在撰写有关好莱坞罢工的文章时，创造了<i>“高管无知”</i>一词来解释娱乐界正在发生的事情。 “好莱坞的首席执行官看到了 Netflix 的成功，竞相复制一种模式，但不知道这种模式是否可持续，这种模式依赖于工会人才不断生产新的（且昂贵的）娱乐内容，”她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">解释道</a>。 “他们对企业的看法是错误的，但更错误的是他们认为劳工会遵守规定。”我打电话给索奇特尔，询问娱乐业高管是如何犯下如此错误的，以及她和她的罢工同事现在是否感到充满希望。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔·法塔尔：</b>高管们在全力投入流媒体业务时犯下的重大错误是什么？<br><br> <b>Xochitl Gonzalez：</b>我记得特别是在新冠疫情期间，显然这些事情一直在进行中，但突然间每个人都在竞相推出流媒体平台。那时，我正在对我的处女作小说进行试点改编<i>。</i>我的第一个想法是，<i>这如何可持续？</i>这看起来不像是一个可行的模型，更不用说一次又一次地匹配了。<br><br>现在，高管们意识到这种模式并不能赚钱，这一点我并不否认。我认为，当你看到高管们获得如此丰厚的报酬时，很难说你会破产或破产，更搞笑的是，即使是外行人也能看出这将是一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/03/why-subscriptions-are-hard-to-cancel/623885/">难以跟上的模式</a>。现在，高管们表示，他们付不起人才的工资。但他们设计了一种利用合同的模式——本质上，这是演员和编剧一直通过剩余报酬获得报酬的一种变通办法。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔：</b>解释一下解决方法。<br><br> <b>Xochitl：</b>例如， <i>《老友记》</i>中的演员们非常富有，因为<i>《老友记》</i>在各个不同的地方都获得了许可，并且可以在有线电视和广播电视上观看。现在<i>《老友记》</i>在 Max 上播出，演员们在该平台上的收入就少了很多。过去，没有人对这样的想法有实质性的异议：如果一部剧收视率很高，编剧和演员就应该看到其中的一部分，因为它是我们创作的。这不是我们引入的新想法。我们只是试图纠正<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/mandy-moore-residuals-sag-aftra-strike-1235538930/#recipient_hashed=7b2a08444fba33a6c4d3b1925c6b91b0e7d0c6fb0d714a3d66f9b34ae571dd0d&amp;recipient_salt=e7bd5c9471e7b1b6f7c359351da66603f51296e3e4776c29585879bad446bb77">新系统</a>利用漏洞的方式。<br><br><b>伊莎贝尔：</b>你对罢工有希望吗？<br><br><b>索奇特尔：</b>我愿意。 SAG 和 WGA 的很多关注点都有重叠。我认为很多人并不总是意识到这一点——对于美国演员工会来说尤其如此——但很多能够以演员或编剧谋生的人都是中产阶级。大部分人都没有赚到钱。这些问题如此关乎生存，这一事实让人们更加坚定。上次<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/11/what-reagan-did-for-hollywood/248391/">我们一起罢工</a>时，我们取得了绝对历史性的成果。所以我感到充满希望，但短期内我感到担忧。洛杉矶有一家食品银行，为美国演员工会会员提供价值超过 300 美元的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CuxXUpHSQUG/?img_index=1">免费食品杂货</a>。有些人需要这些免费的杂货；这是一个挑战。<br><br>我认为当地的人们会坚持下去，因为这不仅仅是因为你的工作而受到重视。问题在于，我们是否确保这是一个可持续发展的职业？我想这会变得血腥。它会对地面上的人造成很大的伤害。但最终，我觉得我们会赢。主要是因为，正如我在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">写WGA</a>时所说，没有我们、没有故事、没有表演，那还有什么？<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">商人打破了好莱坞。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">思考好莱坞编剧罢工的四种方式</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>前总统特朗普表示，他收到一封信， <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/special-counsel-informs-trump-target-probe-efforts-overturn/story?id=101404037">通知他</a>自己是特别检察官杰克·史密斯调查企图推翻2020年总统选举的目标，这创造了再次起诉的可能性。</li><li>一名美军士兵<a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/north-korea-us-national-american-crosses-border-demilitarized-zone-dmz-tour/">脱离</a>边境旅游团闯入朝鲜；据信他已被拘留。</li><li>根据新闻媒体获得的一封电子邮件，德克萨斯州公共安全部的医护人员<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/18/us/texas-troopers-migrant-treatment-concerns/index.html">被告知，将</a>试图穿越南部边境进入里奥格兰德河的人们赶走，并在酷热的情况下拒绝给他们供水。</li><strong>快讯</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/work-in-progress/"><b>正在进行的工作</b></a><b>：</b><b> </b><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homelessness-housing-crisis/674737/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯写道</a>，加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。它暗示了无家可归的根本原因。</li> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">在这里探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br><strong>晚读</strong><br><br>语音机器人让我无言以对<br><br><em>萨希尔·德赛</em><br><br><p>说出我的名字 Saahil Desai 并不难。 Saahil：与<i>锯木厂</i>押韵，或者至少可以让你达到 90%。 Desai：就像<i>决定</i>把最后一点砍掉。确实如此。</p><p>然而，我的名字常常会被淹没在一大堆失态和错误中。最常见的一个，Sa <i>-heel</i> ，至少是一个诚实的尝试——不像它的突变双胞胎，一个单音节的混乱，听起来像<i>海豹。</i>其他人则违背了所有可能的逻辑。有一次，一位大学同学读到我的名字，停顿了一下，然后自信地说：“嗨，西雅图。”</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">如何兑换社交媒体</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/athens-greece-wildfires-residents-flee-photos/674741/">照片：希腊雅典郊外野火肆虐。</a></li><strong>文化突破</strong><br><br><b>读。</b>小说家黛博拉·利维的最新作品<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/august-blue-deborah-levy/9780374602048?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《奥古斯特·布鲁》</i></a>继续<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/august-blue-deborah-levy-novel/674740/">其职业生涯中</a>寻找真实的自我。<br><br><b>手表。</b>伪纪录片<b> </b><i>戏剧营</i>（现已在剧院上映）是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/theater-camp-movie-review/674712/">对创造力的一首可爱的颂歌</a>，并提醒人们艺术社区的重要性。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br> <em>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-strike-2023-streaming/674748/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-strike-2023-streaming/674748/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Donald Trump’s ‘Horrifying News’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位前总统表示，他预计将再次被司法部起诉，这次的指控与 1 月 6 日有关。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EXUymmeWjevA4iV9mqdMuumPbTM=/0x66:3514x2043/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1439325943/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普戴着 MAGA 帽子的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>赢得麦克纳米/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>尽管唐纳德·特朗普有时被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bostonglobe.com/2023/04/04/opinion/another-teflon-don-finally-gets-scratched-court/">特氟隆唐</a>”——这个标签不仅与他自己的名字有关，而且与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/08/trump-gravano-gotti-mafia/568273/">他的作案手法</a>有关——但事实并不是他逃脱了一切后果，而是他最令人震惊的行为。他曾<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/e-jean-carroll-verdict/674001/">在诽谤案中败诉</a>，他的公司因<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/09/ny-attorney-general-trump-organization-was-fraud/671500/">逃税</a>而受到指责，他还被指控犯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-indictment-arrignment-speech/673616/">有错综复杂的商业犯罪</a>。但他犯下的最大罪行——尤其是试图窃取 2020 年总统选举的胜利——却没有受到惩罚。<br><br>这种模式可能很快就会被打破。特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110735295720085796">今天早上发表声明</a>称，他周日晚上收到了司法部特别顾问杰克·史密斯的一封“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/archives/jm/criminal-resource-manual-160-sample-target-letter">目标信</a>”。他说史密斯给了他四天的时间向大陪审团报告，调查特朗普试图颠覆 2020 年大选和 2021 年 1 月 6 日国会大厦骚乱。此类信件通常是起诉书的前奏。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：文书工作的妙招</a><br><br>特朗普并不是最可靠的消息来源。他是个顽固的骗子，三月份错误地声称他即将在纽约的一桩案件中被捕——事实证明，他被捕了，但直到一段时间后才被捕。尽管如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/07/18/us/trump-jan-6-letter#trump-jan-6-letter">一些</a>媒体已经从其他消息<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/special-counsel-informs-trump-target-probe-efforts-overturn/story?id=101404037">来源</a>证实特朗普收到了这封信，而且这一消息与史密斯调查的已知情况相符。<br><br>如果可以合理地假设特朗普确实可能被指控犯有与 1 月 6 日相关的罪行，那么这仍然留下了很大的疑问。其中最重要的是这些可能是什么犯罪。传闻中的可能性包括<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/04/12/trump-fundraising-fraud-special-counsel/">筹款违规</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/28/us/politics/jan-6-prosecutors-trump-fund-raising.html">电汇欺诈</a>等检方惯用手段，甚至叛乱——这是一种极其罕见的指控，但众议院调查委员会 1 月 6 日将一项指控<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/january-6-committee-criminal-referral-donald-trump/672514/">提交</a>给了司法部。<br><br>史密斯可以选择对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">文件政变</a>的许多参与者提出广泛的指控，这将是一个更复杂的案件，但很可能会被定罪，或者他可以更狭隘地关注特朗普或一小部分助手，这可能是一个情况更简单，但在政治上更具煽动性。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：唐纳德·特朗普可能即将被起诉的指南</a><br><br>特朗普发现自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">在全国各地的司法管辖区陷入了法律麻烦</a>，以至于他的律师上周在要求联邦法院推迟对机密文件处理不当的审判时引用了这些麻烦。 （史密斯上个月在该案中起诉了特朗普。）在曼哈顿，这位前总统面临的指控主要是向一名自称与他发生性关系的成人电影演员支付封口费。人们普遍预计佐治亚州富尔顿县地方检察官将在 8 月的某个时候提出与 2020 年选举相关的指控。<br><br>这些案件可以沿着两个轴绘制：定罪概率和犯罪严重性。犯罪就是犯罪，但曼哈顿案相对来说是小事，一些法律观察家认为检方的法律理论值得怀疑。文件案不仅非常严重——它涉及一些对国家安全最敏感的材料——而且事实相对简单，对特朗普来说也是毁灭性的。富尔顿县案件很严重，因为它涉及颠覆选举的企图，但也仅限于佐治亚州的行动；降低定罪的可能性具有挑战性。<br><br>但与 1 月 6 日相关的潜在联邦案件可能是最重要的案件。这些罪行再严重不过了：特朗普首先通过法律和政治计划，然后更绝望地通过武力来挫败选民的意愿。从来没有哪位总统如此直接地攻击美国民主的基础。相比之下，即使是尼克松的罪行也显得黯然失色。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：特朗普为避免起诉而进行的最后一搏</a><br><br>通俗地说，特朗普显然有罪。每个人都看着他声称他赢得了一场他没有赢得的选举。他们听到他向包括佐治亚州议员布拉德·拉芬斯佩格在内的官员施压，要求为他争取选票。他们听说他在 1 月 6 日煽动骚乱。他的行为非常恶劣，以至于众议院对他进行了弹劾，大多数参议员，包括一些共和党人，投票判定有罪——尽管仍低于定罪所需的三分之二。<br><br>然而，有些事情可能用普通话来说是明显正确的，但仍然具有挑战性或无法向陪审团证明。 “你和我都知道，这不是秘密，但在法庭上，在有争议的听证会上，用可接受的证据，排除合理怀疑来证明这一点要困难得多，”前联邦检察官保罗·罗森茨威格(Paul Rosenzweig)早些时候告诉我今年。二月，特朗普发布了一份备忘录<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">，列出了他可能对与骚乱相关的任何指控进行辩护的理由</a>。在今天的声明中，他将针对他的案件描述为“选举干涉”，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/trump-calls-china-interfere-2020-election/599365/">“我是橡皮，你是胶水</a>”肆无忌惮的惊人例子。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment-unsealed/674353/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：可以想象到的最愚蠢的犯罪</a><br><br>政治敏感性也是不可避免的。无论史密斯指控什么，这都将是史无前例的。特朗普将在选举期间对这些指控提出异议。他的律师已经在寻求将文件案的审判<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-wants-use-his-campaign-escape-prosecution/674672/">推迟到 2024 年大选之后</a>，如果他获胜，他很可能能够命令司法部结案。<br><br>所有这些因素意味着没有人可以自信地预测定罪，更不用说监禁了。但与 1 月 6 日相关的目标信将是追究特朗普对美国的罪行负责的首批具体步骤之一。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 15:15:07 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Root Cause of the Homelessness Crisis]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/9xDFDUsEn1ZSw2w_-GO9zCLrUzg=/0x24:4799x2723/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1238537050/original.jpg" alt="2022 年 2 月 16 日，加利福尼亚州洛杉矶市中心附近，收容无家可归者的帐篷在关闭的店面前排成一排。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>弗雷德里克·J·布朗/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>美国 30% 的无家可归者和 50% 的无家可归者居住在加利福尼亚州，总数超过 170,000 人。无家可归<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/01/homelessness-affordable-housing-crisis-democrats-causes/672224/">主要是更广泛的住房负担能力危机的结果</a>，而这又主要是地方政府在最需要的地方建造新住房的难度的结果。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/BenBayer/status/1634194893579984900?s=20">专家</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://reason.com/podcast/2022/01/12/michael-shellenberger-how-progressives-ruined-american-cities/">政客</a>经常声称，加州无家可归危机实际上是人们为了更好的天气或更好的公共福利而离开其他州的结果。但新的研究对这一理论提出了质疑。上个月，加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。它包含来自加州 3,200 名无家可归者的调查数据以及对其中 300 多名无家可归者的深入采访。<br><br>接受调查的无家可归者绝大多数是当地人，而不是来自远方的移民：90% 的人失去了在加利福尼亚州的最后一个住房，75% 的人在他们经历无家可归的同一县失去了它。在 10% 来自其他地方的人中，30% 出生在加利福尼亚州。其他大多数人都有家庭或雇佣关系，或者以前曾在该州居住过。<br><br>退一步来说，数以万计的人在无家可归后搬到加州的想法毫无意义。搬家很贵。失去住房的人很少有办法在全国范围内运送自己、家人、宠物和财物。抛开这一点不谈，无家可归使人们变得脆弱。第一本能不是搬到新的地方，而是留在家人和朋友网络以及潜在的工作机会附近。<br><br>研究人员小心翼翼地确定受访者的来源，但没有促使他们给出任何一个答案。 “我们没有说，‘嘿，你来自加利福尼亚州吗？’”该研究的首席研究员、贝尼奥夫无家可归者和住房计划主任玛戈特·库谢尔告诉我。她说，受访者被要求回顾他们的生活史，解释导致他们无家可归的情况。在此过程中，他们被要求澄清关键的地理细节。<br><br>例如，这是她与我分享的一次交流：<br><br><p>采访者：那你当时（第一次失去住房）几岁？</p><p>回答者：我33岁了。</p><p>采访者：三十三，好吧。那是在这儿，还是在哪儿？</p><p>受访者：那实际上是在加利福尼亚州的波莫纳。</p><p>采访者：波莫纳，好的。然后你一直呆在那里吗？你无家可归之后发生了什么？你的转变是什么？</p><p>受访者：嗯，我有点跳来跳去，但在地理位置上并不是很多。我有点摇摆不定，只是因为，就像我说的，我根本不知道如何应对无家可归的情况。我以前从未无家可归过。我感觉不舒服。我正在努力寻找睡觉的地方。每次他们把你赶走时，你都会说：“好吧，我不能睡在那里，所以我就去这里吧。”所以，事情就是这样发生的。我最终来到了一个叫克莱蒙特的城市……还有另一个克莱蒙特实际上就在波莫纳附近。这就是我住的地方，在波莫纳和克莱蒙特、安大略省[奇诺]之间来回穿梭。它的地理面积不是很大，但技术上是不同的城市。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：您[无家可归]之前住在哪里？</p><p>受访者：加利福尼亚州圣贝纳迪诺。我妈妈的房子有五间卧室。她在那里住了50年零14天。</p><p>采访者：你妈妈的房子，好吧。你离开那所房子回到这里。</p><p>对方：就走开了。</p><p>记者：是因为她去世了吗？</p><p>受访者：不，因为我的家人很恶魔而且很可怕。我们应该哀悼她，而他们只是来看看能从房子里得到什么和其他东西。所以，我就离开了，因为事情不应该是这样的。我哥哥因为照顾我妈妈、殴打我等等而让我住院三次。我原谅他们；我想继续前进。无家可归只是一个停留；你给汽车充电，充电，然后重新上路。我生命中最美好的部分就是我生命的下一部分。就是这样。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到这里的？那么你在德克萨斯州；你有房子。</p><p>回答者：我有房子。我得了癌症，肾癌。我失去了工作，失去了房子……</p><p>采访者：你在休斯顿做什么——什么样的工作？</p><p>受访者：我当了20年卡车司机。</p><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到加州的呢？</p><p>受访者：我来自加利福尼亚州。于是我就回到了家。</p>加利福尼亚州是大多数无家可归者的<em>家园</em>。最常报告的失去住房的原因是由于失业或工作时间减少而导致收入减少。其次是经济原因，其次是两个社会原因：居民之间的冲突，以及对室友或家庭成员施加压力的担忧。在一个更负担得起的环境中，这些社会原因只会导致地址的改变，而不是无家可归。<br><br>通过提前识别高危人群来防止无家可归是非常困难的。部分原因是，处于不稳定局势中的人们比真正失去家园的人们要大得多，而且正如报告所揭示的那样，当人们确实失去家园时，这种情况发生得非常快。签订租约的受访者平均提前 10 天收到他们将失去住房的通知。 60% 没有租约的人报告中位数只有一天。这并不是联系社会服务机构寻求帮助的宽限期。<br><br>然而库舍尔强调，一些无家可归的现象是可以预见的。许多人因监狱或看守所而变得无家可归——占受访者的 19%。更重要的是，67% 的受访者入狱时无家可归。然而，只有不到 20% 的人表示在退出时获得了福利、医疗保健或住房支持。库舍尔表示，阻止加州新一轮无家可归者的流动是“轻而易举的事”：“我们知道人们在哪里；我们知道他们会发生什么。”<br><br>一旦人们失去了家园，搬进新家就变得极具挑战性。受访者表示，距离上次拥有住房的时间中位数为 22 个月。近 90% 的受访者表示，住房成本影响了他们摆脱无家可归的能力。一位受访者表示：“我曾尝试自己寻找公寓，但我想确保自己能买得起。而他们中的大多数人，他们想要三倍的租金。仅就单间公寓或一间卧室而言，价格为 1,100 美元、1,200 美元，仅此而已。我说，‘哇’，你知道吗？这意味着我必须赚到 3,300 美元。我并没有这么做。而且我不会很快做到这一点。”<br><br>超过一半的受访者表示，他们<em>能</em>负担得起的住房距离工作或医疗保健太远，不安全，没有公共交通服务，或者距离孩子或家人太远。受访者还提到了住房歧视、在寻找合适的经济适用住房方面缺乏支持、住房等待时间长达数年、缺乏住房券以及药物滥用（包括在街上使用药物保持清醒和警惕）等障碍。<br><br>无家可归就像慢慢地从山上滚下来。在某人跌倒（或失去住房）后立即是提供帮助的最佳时机：在他们经历创伤和不稳定事件<em>之前</em>。在他们出现或恶化药物滥用问题<em>之前</em>。在他们用尽家人和朋友愿意提供的所有帮助<em>之前</em>。在他们上班迟到太多次，或者没有干净衣服上班<em>之前</em>。<br><br>但即使是一个运作良好、资金充足、及早干预的无家可归机构也无法结束无家可归危机，因为无家可归危机就是<em>家庭</em>危机。<br><br>对于即将从与大家庭共同居住的过度拥挤的公寓中被驱逐的人来说，房屋的中位价意味着什么？实际上很多。一条住房链连接着低收入住房、中等收入住房和高收入住房。当新的市场价格单位首次推出并且人们搬进其中时，这会释放他们以前居住的房屋（通常较旧）的空间。当新住房<em>没有</em>投放市场时，高收入居民就会转向旧住房，从而抬高价格。反过来，中等收入工人转向低收入住房单元，底层的每个人都挤在数量不断减少的经济适用房中，直到有人失去自己的位置。<br><br>加州和全国其他昂贵的州推迟建造更多住房的每一天，都会有一个未来的家庭流落街头。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 13:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[In Praise of Phone Numbers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>互联网提供了许多新的沟通方式，但没有什么比 10 位数的电话号码更重要的了。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/a52YFmgtdZ3O1Ip79Zxz6dKtA6E=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/phone_numbers/original.png" alt="一只手拿着手机" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/《大西洋月刊》插图</figcaption></figure>想象一下一种简单、通用且无需软件更新的技术。它是一串数字，每个部分都充当一组精确的坐标 - 如此基本和优雅，以至于您的曾祖父母可以使用它。将数字按正确的顺序排列，这项技术就会立即触发一点魔力：几秒钟前还一片寂静，触觉上一片空白，突然之间，数英里甚至是大陆之外，突然爆发出一阵美妙的声音或振动。然后，如果你幸运的话，你会听到一个声音，然后你用你的声音回应：你的问题，你沮丧地请求与“代表”交谈！<br><br>自 1879 年以来，电话号码一直以某种形式存在于我们身边，与复写纸、VHS 磁带和随身听不同，它尚未过时。尽管现在有数十种联系方式，但很少有像拿起电话一样持久可靠。一个快速的思维实验：假设你刚刚遭遇了车祸，或者，上帝保佑，发现自己真的处于紧急情况——你会发短信寻求帮助，还是会拨打紧急联系人或 911？尽管我们的大部分身份已经转移到网上，但这些数字序列是与物理世界的模拟联系。当我们创建帐户或需要向任何给定的机器和网络系统证明我们的身份时，我们使用数字字符串作为身份验证手段。<br><br>但电话号码不仅是技术领域的自耕农——一种谦虚、实用的主力——它也是一块重要的文化试金石。我一直是一个没有国家的人；由于童年时的搬迁和成年后普遍的不安，他有幸收养了许多家乡，从曼哈顿到蒙大拿州的米苏拉。尽管我在徘徊，但我的地方感和我身份的一个重要方面却永远固定下来，这要归功于三个简单的号码： <em>610</em> ，这是“费城郊区”的总机电话<em>。</em> “我在那里只住了十年，但就是在那时我碰巧得到了我的第一部手机。因此，我的区号为我提供了类似于巧妙伪装甚至护照的东西。偶然发现另一个 610 号码就像打开一扇门一样。<em>你来自哪个城镇？噢，真的，你在哪里上学？</em>三位数可以把陌生人变成同路人。<br><br>电话号码，太棒了！一个伟大的发明，十分之十，没有注释！<em>打电话给 JG 温特沃斯！ 877-立即现金！ 800-588-2300，帝国（今天）！</em>如果没有电话号码我们会在哪里？无聊的？丢失的？穿着缠腰布，在明火上烤新鲜猎取的肉？ 2003 年的一天，我无意中走出了一个热门话题，走进普鲁士国王购物中心的一家 Cingular Wireless 商店，看到了一个几乎是随机的 10 位数指示符，这让我不禁感到有点浪漫。我仍然习惯在凌晨 1 点登录我的银行，联系兽医，并在我的群聊中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/realteaemoji/status/1679173275002322972?s=20">发送令人不安的人工智能生成的 TikTok</a> ，这就是持久力<em>和</em>多功能性。<br><br>在我 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/cwarzel/status/1641161893904793600">发布</a>关于电话号码在我们生活中所扮演的角色的推文后，许多人回复并分享了他们自己的观点。电话号码可以标志着一个新的场合，就像一位名叫 Austin McKinley 的用户所做的那样，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thebadcode/status/1641514561009483776?s=20">告诉</a>我，他 2008 年搬到旧金山时做的第一件事就是购买一部 iPhone 并获得一个本地电话号码。 “旧的生活结束了，新的生活开始了，”他写道。在缅因州（以及我以前的蒙大拿州）等地方，区号可能意味着国家自豪感。 “拥有非 207 号码是局外人的直接信号，”推特用户、迈纳州人本·斯普拉格 (Ben Sprague) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/bensprague/status/1641167129645809664?s=20">告诉</a>我。 “那些远离区号歧视的人有祸了。”一个好的号码也可以是与过去的情感纽带，因为它适用于一位位于费城、名叫艾米的用户，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/theHollandaise/status/1641164293746958336?s=20">告诉</a>我，她在母亲去世时继承了她的号码。我的朋友约翰在推特上的昵称是约翰尼·勇气（Johnny Courage），他写道，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/johnnycourage/status/1641296385361301504?s=20">保留</a>了自己的 919 区号，以“保持我在卡罗来纳州的真诚和南方侨民身份”。 “当然，这是昨天的古雅遗迹。但它把我和家联系在一起。”<br><br>这些老式的乐趣并不意味着电话号码没有随着时间的推移而演变。正如我的同事梅根·加伯 (Megan Garber) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">在 2014 年所写的那样</a>，电话号码最初是服务于较小地理区域的特殊字母数字地址（例如，她写道，MU 5-9975 会将您引导至总机代理，然后由该代理将您与纽约市默里山 (Murray Hill) 社区）。随着电话越来越普及，手动总机系统变得自动化，号码系统从地区性转向全国性，号码组更长，并引入了区号。每次编号系统扩展时，我们都会抱怨，但它仍然持续存在——北美当前的 10 位编号系统于 1997 年在马里兰州<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/23/technology/the-10-or-11-digit-local-call-fosters-anxiety-and-shrugs.html">推出</a>，我们没有回头。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">阅读：区号的演变</a><br><br>但即使是 10 位数字系统（我生活中的技术常数之一）也有过期日期。在某些时候，这些数字将会耗尽，这一认识让我想知道谁（如果有人）在密切关注我们的数字。值得庆幸的是，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nationalnanpa.com/about_us/index.html">北美编号计划管理员（North American Numbering Plan Administrator）</a>是一个令人愉快的官僚组织，负责管理和分配 20 个国家/地区的电话号码和区号。假设一大群人搬到蒙大拿州或缅因州并申请新号码，NANPA 的高级主管 Florence Weber 告诉我，NANPA 的团队与运营商和州委员会合作推出新的区号，这个过程至少需要三年时间。<br><br> “我们继续看到对数字的请求不断增加，而且这种情况不会消失，”韦伯说。但没有什么是永恒的。 NANPA 一直在密切关注并为我们用完三位数区号或必须超越 10 位数区号的那一天做好准备。韦伯告诉我，根据 NANPA 的专有预测系统（该系统考虑了预测需求和分配率），“预计用尽日期”是 2051 年的某个时间。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1880/06/a-telephonic-conversation/306078/">马克·吐温：一次电话交谈（1880 年 6 月起）</a><br><br>一想到那天会发生什么，我就不寒而栗。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/are-12-digit-phone-numbers-in-our-future/">更长的电话号码</a>的出现是一种可能性。屈服于在线服务是另一回事。电话号码感觉有点像 Zoom 会议、一键式 FaceTiming、WhatsApp、Signal、Viber、DM、Discord 等时代的遗物。电话号码最初被认为是一种通过位置路由连接的方式，从技术上讲，互联网现在也可以通过 IP 地址或使用互联网语音协议来实现这一点。书呆子们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pocketnow.com/why-are-we-still-using-phone-numbers/">建议</a>我们可以放弃编号系统，而使用去中心化的呼叫系统，其工作方式有点像网址——你获得一个唯一的地址并购买一个域名，这样人们就可以联系你，而无需输入一长串号码。<br><br>尽管如此，如果我们的区号、前缀和线路号码被时间的沙子慢慢冲走，我们会失去什么，这是值得考虑的。如果没有更多的话，值得欣赏这些数字——一系列非个人的半随机数字，一旦它们属于你，就会获得新的生命。当共享时，电话号码是最亲密的邀请，提供无限的联系可能性。它为我们停泊并引导我们。仅此一点就是一个值得庆祝的小奇迹。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastruct/674735/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastruct/674735/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is Tennessee a Democracy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当共和党获得绝对多数控制权并不满意时会发生什么<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/27TF7e4XH-or1LtfF2cywj_n4xQ=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/17/TheAtlantic_Tennessee_1_jul23_rt/original.jpg" alt="红色的田纳西州议会大厦" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>里卡多·托马斯为《大西洋月刊》拍摄的照片插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br><span class="smallcaps">沿着纳什维尔北部远郊</span>的外缘行驶，经过可能是谷仓或可能是婚礼场地的建筑，围绕葡萄园格罗夫或新希望村的开发项目，最终您将到达本应成为公司新总部的地方。田纳西州萨姆纳县选举委员会。这是一个毫无特色的单层砖砌仓库，附有一些临时办公室，空间只够容纳极少数选举委员会员工、他们最近购买的 275 台投票机，或许还可以容纳一些过去与他们共用房间的维护人员。那时，该机构还在县政府大楼的地下室里。<br><br>布满灰尘的野餐桌靠在墙上。一所小学就在几百米开外。这座建筑或其位置没有什么引起“争议”的。但当去年萨姆纳县的地方选举中一个自称宪政共和党的派别上台时，它却变成了这样。<br><br>为了充分理解这个故事，你需要明白美国政治两极分化的标准形式在萨姆纳并不存在，萨姆纳是一个农村但迅速郊区化的县，民主党根本不参与其中。二十多年来，没有人赢得任何县公职。相反，立宪共和党赢得了县委员会 17 个席位中的 14 个（在大选中只有 15% 的合格选民参加了投票），他们的主要对手是普通共和党人，或者正如他们的对手所说的那样他们，RINO（“名义上的共和党人”）。宪法共和党的网站解释说，绿诺组织与他们自己不同：“他们提高税收，他们投票让公民保持沉默，他们不会保护私有财产权。他们经常与民主党合作，击败像我们这样真正的宪政共和党人。”<br><br>接管县委员会后，立宪共和党<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/election-conspiracies-local-government-religion-republicans-tennessee-758307fb4856c91138c085ad70505841">发布了一份文件，</a>正式宣布他们的活动将“反映建国之初固有的犹太基督教价值观”。他们还关闭了人力资源部门，试图将一栋公共历史建筑私有化，并拒绝支付选举委员会搬迁至砖砌建筑的费用，尽管这是上届政府同意的。旧办公室（最近被洪水淹没的三个地下室）太小，无法存放新的投票机，而且也不安全。我去的那天，地下室的入口就在收银窗口旁边，有几十个人在排队缴税。县专员对这些论点不为所动。 “如果我们不资助它，你就不能这样做，”县委员会的宪法共和党人之一杰里米·曼斯菲尔德(Jeremy Mansfield)在去年秋天的一次公开会议上向选举委员会介绍了这一举措。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYzcIZXfkmI">6 月的一次会议</a>上，另一位县专员因新投票机已交付到新大楼而感到愤怒，他表示，尽管他“不愿意拿出王牌”，但该委员会总是可以“宣布这笔财产剩余，并出售”它。”这将使选举委员会及其机器无处可去。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-induced-idiocy-tennessee/673726/">彼得·韦纳：田纳西州特朗普主义的猛烈攻击</a><br><br>这座建筑似乎是一件值得大惊小怪的小事。但脸书上的帖子和公开会议的视频都可以在网上查看——立宪共和党人非常透明——清楚地表明这不是一个微不足道的管辖权纠纷，这些人也不是小人。他们的野心和兴趣远远超出了他们的县域。他们的 Facebook 页面对唐纳德·特朗普最新起诉的消息作出反应，宣称“拜登家族是一个有组织的犯罪家族”，“我们的司法系统被操纵来对付特朗普”。另一篇帖子询问田纳西州是否“应该脱离联邦”。更重要的是，曼斯菲尔德没有回应我的采访请求（他对媒体的看法在他的 Facebook 页面上很清楚，有人将美联社称为“美国真理报”，他回答说，“除了《真理报》做了更诚实的报道”），二月份写了一篇长文攻击提前投票和投票机：“选举公正性的黄金标准是由人们填写纸质选票，并在选举日由当地选区的人们进行计票。”<br><br>立宪共和党人对这些观点充满信心是有原因的。 “我们的信仰源自圣经，”他们的网站宣称：“我们在每次聚会上祈祷，并在我们所做的一切事情中寻求上帝！他的智慧指导着我们的决定。”同样的来源让他们相信他们的敌人是错误的。曼斯菲尔德在脸书上写道：“邪恶永不停歇。”是好的，也是对的。”<br><br>这些雄心勃勃的目标很少是他们能够实现的。萨姆纳县专员无法逮捕乔·拜登总统。他们不能脱离。但该县的选举委员会就在那里，其成员由两党州选举委员会任命。这是他们不喜欢的更广泛文化和他们不信任的政府的当地体现。如果他们能让该机构回到容易发生洪水的地下室，他们就会这么做。<br><br>萨姆纳选举委员会的律师汤姆·李（该委员会目前正在起诉该县）也有一个额外的解释。李指出，立宪共和党人上任时希望实施深刻的革命性变革。这意味着，无论前政权做出什么决定，他们都会反对：“他们上台后说，‘我们之前的一切都不算数。我们代表了一些新的、不同的东西，我们不必效忠于过去。”我告诉他，这听起来像是布尔什维克和其他革命者所使用的语言。他没有笑。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">大多数时候</span>，田纳西州的政治不会成为全国新闻。这种情况在四月份发生了变化，当时田纳西州众议院共和党绝对多数派的领导人驱逐了两名民主党议员贾斯汀·琼斯和贾斯汀·皮尔逊。这两个人被指控扰乱诉讼程序，因为他们在休会期间使用扩音器在会议厅的地板上重复了枪支管制活动人士的要求。<br><br>该事件引起了轩然大波。这种惩罚似乎既极端——自重建以来，只有两人被田纳西州立法机关开除，一人因贿赂，另一人因涉嫌性行为不当——而且是种族主义的，因为它故意针对两名年轻的黑人男子。第三位抗议者是白人众议员格洛丽亚·约翰逊，她被允许保留她的众议院席位。做出这一决定的共和党人后来意识到这看起来很糟糕。在随后举行的一次激烈的会议上（当地在线出版物<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tnholler.com/2023/04/leaked-audio-tn-house-gop-caucus-infighting-over-tn-3-votes/"><i>《田纳西</i><i>州霍勒报</i>》泄露了该会议</a>的录音带），他们对驱逐事件并不表示遗憾，但他们确实斥责了一名成员没有投票驱逐约翰逊，理由是：把她排除在外让他们看起来都是种族主义者。这一决定也让抗议者成为英雄，他们现在被称为“田纳西三人组”，这个称号之前曾授予约翰尼·卡什的后备乐队。琼斯和皮尔逊被地方官员恢复职务，等待八月份的特别选举，并立即成为全国明星。<br><br>但事实上，他们的故事并不是从那天开始的。不久前，田纳西州不仅是一个两党合作程度更高的州，而且还是两党合作的<i>典范</i>，为其他国家树立了榜样。田纳西<i>州</i>报纸的专栏作家基尔·亨特（也是一名民主党人，曾为共和党州长拉马尔·亚历山大工作过）写了一本关于 20 世纪 80 年代和 90 年代的书，当时温和派民主党人和自由派共和党人统治该州；当田纳西州派出亚历山大、霍华德·贝克、阿尔·戈尔和吉姆·震荡波进入美国参议院时；当时做出的许多决定为田纳西州当前的投资热潮铺平了道路。这本书的名字是<i>《跨越过道：两党合作如何将田纳西州带入二十一世纪并拯救美国》</i> 。亨特告诉我，自那时以来发生了很多变化，这本书“现在可能符合讣告的资格”。<br><br>今天，田纳西州是一党统治的典范。它有一位共和党州长和立法机构。共和党任命的人掌管州最高法院。该州的美国众议院代表团由 9 名成员组成，其中包括 8 名共和党人；田纳西州已派出两名共和党人进入参议院。州长是全州唯一当选的官员。与其他州不同的是，田纳西州的总检察长和国务卿是任命的，而且都是共和党人。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/america-democracy-autocracy-laboratories/673751/">布莱恩·克拉斯：红州正在尝试独裁主义</a><br><br>这种情况也不容易改变，因为不公正划分选区在该州是一种血腥运动。仍然是蓝色的纳什维尔市在国会只有一位民主党代表，但当 2022 年选举前重新绘制地图时，共和党立法者将纳什维尔分为三个延伸到乡村的地区。每人选出一名共和党人。纳什维尔现在的代表不再是担任该席位二十年的蓝狗温和派民主党人吉姆·库珀，而是安迪·奥格尔斯等人，他最出名的是寄出一张印有他自己、孩子和妻子的节日贺卡。在圣诞树前拿着枪。州一级的选区划分也同样恶毒——约翰逊认为，一次选区重新划分包括一项将她排除在政治之外的特殊努力：“他们分割了我的选区，并在我家周围画了一条基本上几个街区的线，将我从该选区拉出来，”她告诉我。 （她移动，再次奔跑，并获胜。）<br><br>让人们投票也不是那么容易，因为田纳西州有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">一些全国最严格的投票法</a>。您不能晚于选举前 30 天进行投票登记。如果您通过缺席选票投票，选票必须在选举日或之前通过邮件送达。没有投递箱。首次投票的选民必须亲自投票，这对于在州外学习的大学生来说是一个特殊的问题。 2019年，立法机关通过了一项法律<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">，规定选民登记活动人士</a>如果提交太多错误表格，将受到经济或刑事处罚——这一条款似乎旨在阻止投票活动，因违宪而被阻止，后来被废除。也许这些规则本身都不会显得令人难以容忍。但纳什维尔选举委员会的民主党人特里西娅·赫茨菲尔德 (Tricia Herzfeld) 认为，“累积效应”“会让投票变得困难”。这一理论有证据支持：田纳西州要么是全国选民投票率最低的州之一，要么是全国投票率最低的州之一，具体取决于您的统计方式。当然，这甚至是在萨姆纳县剥夺其选举委员会办公空间之前发生的，可以想象，那里的任何人都很难投票。<br><br>我<span class="smallcaps">来到田纳西州的</span>部分原因是我想知道它与波兰和匈牙利的感觉有多么相似，在过去的十年里，我一直在警惕地观察着那里民主的衰落和一党制国家的崛起。在纳什维尔，巨大的差异立即显而易见，那里的音乐是一切的背景，每个人似乎都来自一个聚会或前往一个聚会，政治光谱双方的人们都竭尽全力向我介绍其他人。 “这是一个女婿式的小镇，”有人告诉我。我不太清楚这意味着什么（与每个人照顾朋友和亲戚有关？），但这很有趣。由于这个原因和许多其他原因，纳什维尔不是坎伯兰河畔的布达佩斯。权利法案仍然适用。联邦法官根据田纳西州法律做出裁决。美国宪法受到广泛甚至夸张的尊崇。没有中欧的悲观情绪。<br><br>然而，旨在创造不公平竞争环境的一连串微小的法律和程序变化、执政党莫名其妙的不满情绪、流离失所的温和派无处可去——这在其他地方似乎很熟悉。制度政治已经变得具有表演性，在某种程度上与现实生活脱节的感觉也是如此。毕竟，田纳西三人组在立法机关的地板上进行了抗议，因为在那里展开的谈话没有注意到会议厅外发生的更大规模的抗议活动。几天前，纳什维尔的一所私立基督教学校圣约发生了可怕的大规模枪击事件，震惊了公众。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2023/05/03/vanderbilt-poll-tennessee/">民意调查</a>显示，超过 70% 的田纳西州人希望出台危险信号法律，允许官员从可能滥用枪支的人手中没收枪支，而超过 80% 的人支持背景调查和其他枪支安全法。<br><br>这些绝大多数并没有反映在立法辩论中。 <i>《田纳西州霍勒》杂志</i>的创始人兼编辑贾斯汀·卡纽告诉我，学校枪击事件发生后的几天里，一切“一切如常”。卡纽和纳什维尔的许多人一样是来自加利福尼亚州的移民，他本人是田纳西州国会议员的前民主党候选人。在竞选期间，他看到了公众对话中的一个空白，这一经历促使他创立了<i>Holler</i> 。或者更确切地说，Hollers：现在有几个 Twitter 分支——查塔努加 Holler、克拉克斯维尔 Holler 等等——都专注于全州媒体所忽视的超本地化问题。卡纽自己的天赋在于一种竞选新闻形式：他制作短视频片段，通常是州立法者的视频片段，然后在社交媒体上传播。有时它们会像病毒一样传播。这就是田纳西三人抗议那天他所做的事情。 “有成千上万的人出现在国会大厦，”他告诉我，“要求发生一些事情。如果什么都没发生，那会非常令人泄气。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/04/tennessee-expulsions-republican-gop/673709/">阅读：田纳西州的驱逐只是一个开始</a><br><br>这并不是共和党领导层第一次试图结束辩论。众议院的“两个贾斯汀”（现在被称为“两个贾斯汀”）带来了扩音器，正是因为共和党领导层通常会在民主党人讲话时关闭麦克风。众议员博·米切尔（Bo Mitchell）曾对众议院说：“请不要说你是反堕胎者，并在街上放置更多武器”，这一言论被打断，该声明被裁定为侮辱性言论。琼斯告诉我，他在一次委员会会议上被排除在外，因为他说领导层正在“在学校枪击问题上贴创可贴”；几天后，他还被告知必须从夹克上取下<span class="smallcaps">禁止攻击性武器的</span>别针。正如田纳西州众议院多数党领袖威廉·兰伯斯 (William Lamberth) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/NC5PhilWilliams/status/1661524250019201024?s=20">对当地一家电视台所说</a>，共和党人坚持认为，演讲者应该坚持主题：“这不是开放麦克风之夜。”<br><br> “他们上台后说，‘在我们之前发生的一切都不算数。我们代表了一些新的、不同的东西，我们不必效忠于过去。”<br><br>根据相对较新的规定，个别委员的提问时间已从 15 分钟缩短至 5 分钟。有时候，想要提出反对意见的人根本没有被邀请。在一场有关堕胎法案的辩论中，格洛丽亚·约翰逊 (Gloria Johnson) 告诉我，“我在众议院的地板上站了 45 分钟，整个辩论过程都是这样，但他们拒绝见我。”这些策略是新的。断断续续地在立法机构任职十多年的约翰逊告诉我，尽管她2012年加入时众议院也拥有共和党绝对多数，但当时的议长并没有将民主党排除在辩论之外。 “我不记得她拒绝拜访我，”她说。琼斯在当选前曾在纳什维尔担任过十年的社区组织者，他同意以前的演讲者更愿意进行对话。 “这是我见过的最极端的会议，”他说。 “共和党人现在将立法机关视为私人宫殿、兄弟会会所或乡村俱乐部。”<br><br>激进化也不仅仅在立法机构中可见。正如匈牙利的欧尔班·维克多与反对派控制的布达佩斯的斗争（土耳其的雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安与伊斯坦布尔的斗争，波兰的雅罗斯瓦夫·卡钦斯基与华沙的斗争）一样，田纳西州共和党人与反对派控制的纳什维尔的斗争也是如此。在埃利斯顿广场汽水店吃早餐时，纳什维尔市长、民主党人约翰·库珀（也是前国会议员吉姆·库珀的兄弟）喜欢炫耀城市遗址，他列举了该市与州之间的各种争端：一定程度的厌倦：关于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/04/03/faa-intervenes-in-dispute-over-nashville-airport-leadership/70076289007/">机场的控制</a>、关于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.adamsandreese.com/last-call/fate-of-metro-nashville-beer-board-remains-uncertain-at-tennessee-general-assembly">啤酒委员会</a>、关于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/03/09/bills-to-take-over-nashville-airport-sports-authority-boards-advance/69985037007/">体育当局</a>、关于市议会的规模（共和党试图将其成员从 40 名削减到 20 名），以及关于 2024 年共和党全国代表大会——部分由于所有其他争吵，这种争吵不会发生在纳什维尔。<br><br>有些争议只是关于谁控制着资金，但他认为真正的文化摩擦也是这些争议的根源。纳什维尔曾经被市长称为“大县城”，以音乐俱乐部而闻名，现在它也是国际投资、医疗保健投资和科技投资的焦点。甲骨文正在该市建造一个耗资超过 10 亿美元的园区；亚马逊在这里也占有重要地位。我们见面的那天早上，库珀市长刚从库尔德斯坦回来，正在倒时差。他去那里是因为纳什维尔不仅是泰勒·斯威夫特的诞生地，也是美国最大的库尔德社区之一的所在地。早餐后，他开车送我去了东岸，这是该市<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nashville.gov/departments/planning/long-range-planning/local-planning-studies/east-bank-planning-study">下一个重大开发项目</a>的所在地，该项目将包括一个新体育场、新住房和一些基础设施改造；一路上，我们经过了一系列引人注目的建筑工地，里面到处都是巨型起重机。尽管如此，在保守的媒体世界中，纳什维尔的城市领导人只是另一群敌人。福克斯新闻曾用一整段内容来报道库珀， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/virus-outbreak-marsha-blackburn-nashville-tucker-carlson-tennessee-d8370b1bab309d954a8b6b7fb5547d39">塔克·卡尔森在其中错误地指责他</a>隐瞒了有关新冠病毒的信息。<br><br>卡纽（他并不孤单）认为国家是一种“实验品”，是同一个媒体世界中的一个测试市场，一个可以实验性地激发新的文化战争主题的地方。针对法官和远程投票的战争始于 2021 年，当时一个关键众议院小组委员会的主席<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2021/03/02/support-grows-nashville-judge-ellen-hobbs-lyle-targeted-lawmaker/6878391002/">试图罢免一名在大流行期间裁定支持扩大邮寄投票权的法官</a>。去年九月，州长和其他共和党人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/">猛烈抨击范德比尔特大学医学中心</a>，据称该中心镇压批评该大学性别诊所的员工，但该大学否认了这一指控。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/"> </a>最近，州总检察长对该诊所进行了调查， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tennesseelookout.com/2023/06/22/ag-made-sweeping-demands-for-vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-records-as-part-of-fraud-inquiry/?eType=EmailBlastContent&amp;eId=0bdfc350-1039-4564-94e1-7a42e32a226c">要求提供私人医疗记录</a>。<br><br>有时这些努力会被收回。一群坚定的当地律师和游说者帮助为母亲的生命获得了一些例外，并将其纳入该州的堕胎禁令。特朗普任命的一名联邦法官<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/13/opinion/tennessee-trump-maga-justin-jones-pearson.html">最近推翻了</a>另一项文化战争姿态，即田纳西州一项禁止公开变装表演的法律，理由是它压制了言论自由。但个别强硬立法是否坚持可能并不重要，因为通过这些立法的部分目的只是为了让当地政客与同一个保守媒体世界的普遍观点保持一致。 One example: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://trackbill.com/bill/tennessee-senate-joint-resolution-174-memorials-recognition-danube-institute/2353243/">a recent resolution</a> passed by the legislature to “recognize and commend” Orbán&#39;s think tank, the Danube Institute, which promotes illiberal and antidemocratic ideas. Jones, objecting to that resolution, asked Tim Hicks, the Republican who proposed it, if he knew who Orbán was. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thetnholler/status/1648811745064935425?s=46&amp;t=QfucpGynsbxt5jS-672ayA">He did not</a> . One disgruntled Republican described this whole process to me as “governing by anecdote.” You could also describe it as “governing by Fox News.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/01/children-sex-trafficking-conspiracy-epidemic/620845/">From the January/February 2022 issue: The great (fake) child-sex-trafficking epidemic</a><br><br> But every so often, a glimpse of something uglier appears, a hint that some people want more than culture wars designed for TikTok, Twitter, and the evening news. Walking to her home in Nashville, an acquaintance saw a car with a <span class="smallcaps">shoot your local pedophile</span><i> </i>bumper sticker, showing an outline of a man holding a gun to another man&#39;s head. T-shirts with this image, phrasing, and implied approval of violence are for sale online. “This isn&#39;t new to you, but it&#39;s new to us,” she told me, which isn&#39;t quite true. Poland, where I live part of the time, has had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46878325">one political murder</a> in recent years, but it was a knife murder. In Tennessee, people have guns. Jim Cooper, the former member of Congress, told me that getting anyone to run for office as a Democrat in some rural parts of the state is difficult partly because <i>Democrat</i> and <i>pedophile</i> are so often conflated by Republican activists, and potential candidates are spooked. About half of the state-legislature seats were uncontested in 2022.<br><br> Not that the problem of finding Democrats to run for office is new. Cooper also told me that one of his staff used to comb through local newspapers and look for people who had written angry letters to the editor. Then she would call them up and ask them to stand for election. Some said yes. Though most of them lost, he considered that a kind of victory. Jones thinks that after the expulsion crisis, “young people are fired up, bringing urgency to our politics,” and that more candidates will come forward. But there will be a steep road to climb if people fear that what is at stake in their local election is not tax rates and building permits but the safety and even the lives of their children—and if they fight back with real weapons.<br><br> If that possibility sounds ludicrous, or incredible, it shouldn&#39;t. Kanew, the <i>Tennessee Holler</i> editor, woke up one night last April to the sound of gunfire. Someone had shot up the front of his house. No one has yet been arrested.<br><br> “Y <span class="smallcaps">ou know the old saying:</span> All politics is national.” That&#39;s what the mayor of Nashville told me over his ham and eggs. “All politics is national,” several other people said to me too. It&#39;s a joke—“All politics is local” is the old political chestnut—but also not a joke. In the past couple of years, prominent and less-prominent conservatives have been flocking from all over the country to Tennessee and, more precisely, to Williamson County, adjacent to Nashville and, partly thanks to that proximity, now one of the wealthiest counties in the country. The town of Franklin, Williamson&#39;s county seat, has a large and well-lit (I visited at night) monument to the soldiers of the Confederacy. It is also home to equally monumental culture-war clashes and school-board battles that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/23/opinion/school-boards-books-tennessee.html">can rival those anywhere else in the country</a> . The <i>New York Times</i> columnist David French, who lives there, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/06/opinion/maga-america-trump.html">reckons</a> that “only 15 percent of my neighbors are Democrats.” The Daily Wire, a conservative media company that specializes in culture-war clashes and school-board battles, is now based in Nashville, as are a handful of its stars.<br><br> Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should.<br><br> “All politics is national” is also the explanation that a lot of people gave me when I asked how Tennessee went from having a culture of bipartisanship to de facto one-party rule in a mere two decades. Almost everybody wanted to explain that Tennessee politics used to reflect the state&#39;s particular geography (mountains in the east, Mississippi River Delta in the west, rivers and forest in the middle) and complicated history. Some Tennesseans had declared for the Confederacy; others fought against it. The Ku Klux Klan was founded in Pulaski, Tennessee; Nashville was the site of a series of sit-ins that were important to the civil-rights movement. The disgruntled Republicans in particular <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnas.org/publications/blog/two-cheers-for-tennessee">mourn the death</a> of what used to be called “Tennessee enlightened mountain Republicanism,” the liberal, business-oriented party that once challenged the pre-civil-rights “Old South” Democratic one-party state, which relied on Jim Crow and voter suppression. For a long time, both parties celebrated the demise of that system, and no one wanted it back. Or so it seemed.<br><br> By some accounts, the shift began in the 1990s, during the Clinton administration, when talk radio and a confrontational new style of national media began to weaken the local newspapers that people used to read, and the local culture too. Others think the turning point came in the 2000s, when Barack Obama&#39;s presidency produced a racist backlash. In 2012, one poll showed that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/sorry-obama-birtherism-is-alive-and-well-2012-3?IR=T">nearly half of Tennessee Republicans</a> believed in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/05/birtherism-and-trump/610978/">birtherism conspiracy theory</a> .<br><br> Still others think the harder shift inside the Republican Party began more recently, <i>after</i> it gained full control. John Geer, a Vanderbilt political scientist, told me that whenever a supermajority controls a legislature for a long period of time, “those in the minority have no political ability to effect change, and so they stop acting like politicians and instead become activists,” a thesis that explains the actions of the Tennessee Three, as well as the feeling that politics has become a form of performance art, only distantly related to real life.<br><br> But the supermajority is also affected, and its members become activists of a different kind. To stay in office in a state where few people vote and districts are gerrymandered, Tennessee legislators need to appeal to only a tiny number of very dedicated, very partisan people. The competition for those votes can quite quickly turn into a competition for who can sound most radical. Even the minority leader of the Tennessee State Senate, Raumesh Akbari, a Democrat, told me that it&#39;s harder to do deals with people from heavily gerrymandered districts: “You don&#39;t have anybody to check you and your district is extremely partisan.” Her own district skews heavily Democratic and heavily Black. “If I wasn&#39;t someone who was willing to compromise, I wouldn&#39;t have to,” Akbari said.<br><br> There is another element: Call it the lesson of Sumner County, the place where Republicans won everything, control everything, and yet <i>still</i> feel aggrieved and victimized. As in Hungary or Poland or as in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/venezuelas-suffering-shows-where-illiberalism-leads/606988/">Venezuela</a> , the experience of radicalism can make people more radical. Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should. No county commission or state legislature can possibly meet the demands of a quasi-religious movement that believes it has God on its side and that its opponents herald the apocalypse. But that doesn&#39;t mean they give up. It just means they keep trying, using any tool available. Eventually they arrive at the point described by Tom Lee, the lawyer for the Sumner County Election Commission: “It&#39;s not enough to get your majority and get your way—they have to make the minority lose their voice.”<br><br> On the tape leaked to <i>The</i> <i>Tennessee Holler</i> after the expulsion of Pearson and Jones, this dynamic is powerfully revealed. Grim Republican legislators talked about what they think is really at stake, and it isn&#39;t megaphones. “If you don&#39;t believe we are at war for our republic,” one of them says to the group, “with all love and respect to you, you need a different job.” They don&#39;t believe that this is a normal political competition, either, or that their opponents are a normal, legitimate, small- <i>d</i> democratic opposition. Democrats, says another, “are not our friends.” They “destroy our republic and the foundation of who we are.” At one point, an apocalyptic tone creeps into the conversation: “The left wants Tennessee so bad because if they get us, the Southeast falls and it&#39;s &#39;game over&#39; for the republic.” So urgent and so dramatic is this challenge that some of them have come to believe that rules might have to be broken: “You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong,” one of them says.<br><br> <i>You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong. Fight for the republic</i> , <i>because otherwise it will be “game over</i> ”: The language itself wouldn&#39;t be unusual, if this were a radical minority fighting for its very existence. But this is the Republican Party, the party that controls pretty much everything in Tennessee. They are going to win the next election, and probably the one after that. Yet they sound as if winning isn&#39;t enough: They also want their opponents to fall silent, and they are doing what they can to make that happen.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Remote-Work Debate Stays So Heated]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The conversation often foregrounds large-scale issues such as productivity and company culture, but the question of where an employee works is intensely personal. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C9uTFuz-5brHPsAys00WYgH6Pc8=/0x266:5121x3147/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_862664210/original.jpg" alt="People pass a building at night" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Peter Cade / Getty</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br> The physical space in which a person works, or hopes to work, intersects with their most personal choices. Today we&#39;re checking in on the remote-work debate and why it remains so heated.<br><br> First, here are four new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">商人打破了好莱坞。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">Goodbye to the prophets of doom.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/">I have cancer. I can&#39;t put my kids first anymore.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/">Joe Lieberman weighs the Trump risk.</a></li> <strong>Better Together?</strong><br><br> In the summer of 2021, I started going back to the office. It was not the allure of watercooler chatter or the promise of juiced-up productivity that pulled me in. At the time, I just really wanted to sit in the AC. It was June; it was hot. Access to a desk in a freezing-cold Midtown tower—a far cry from my living room, which tended to get steamy on 90-degree Brooklyn days—seemed like a major perk. I was living with roommates, was vaccinated, and had no child-care duties. Each morning, I strapped on my mask and packed my backpack with canisters of coffee and sandwiches to sustain me through the day. I often felt better when I got home: When you&#39;re going into an office, I found, it&#39;s harder to have a day where nothing happens.<br><br> My desire to return to a routine that involved leaving my home was inspired, in part, by my now-colleague Ellen Cushing&#39;s 2021 <i>Atlantic</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/03/what-pandemic-doing-our-brains/618221/">article</a> about what the monotony of the pandemic was doing to our brain. “Sometimes I imagine myself as a Sim, a diamond-shaped cursor hovering above my head as I go about my day. Tasks appear, and I do them. Mealtimes come, and I eat. Needs arise, and I meet them,” she writes in one memorable passage. In another, she quotes an expert saying that “environmental enrichment”—seeing new people, observing new things on a commute—is good for our brain&#39;s plasticity. After reading the article in March 2021, I became fixated on the idea that observing random humans on my commute would keep my mind sharp.<br><br> Then the fall came around, and so did more of my colleagues. It was great to see them. It was also great, sometimes, to return to the relative solitude of my home and take walks in Prospect Park at midday. I was lucky to have that flexibility. Now that I work for <i>The Atlantic</i> , I go into the office almost every day. I have enjoyed meeting new people and, again, sitting in the industrial-grade AC.<br><br> I&#39;ve given you this narration of my personal experience because, for all the talk of productivity and metrics and company culture, the topic of returning to the office is intensely personal. My needs and desires, for a variety of reasons relating to my age, finances, circumstances, health situation, and lifestyle, might be very different from those of workers who fall elsewhere on any of those axes. Some working parents have said they might value flexibility at school-pickup time. Some workers of color have raised the benefit of being free from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://hbr.org/2022/05/research-the-real-time-impact-of-microaggressions">in-office microaggressions</a> . Recent college graduates may want to go into the office to make friends. And of course, not all workers are able to work remotely. The physical space in which one works, or hopes to work, intersects with one&#39;s most personal choices. It collides with and reveals what people value most.<br><br> Nick Bloom, a Stanford economics professor who studies remote work, told me that “research and evidence are slowly catching up” to the work-from-home debate. In five years, he predicted, the topic will be less controversial. Bloom and two colleagues, Jose Maria Barrero and Steven J. Davis, published a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kqbngD8pemqxAkZmWCOQ32Yk6PXK9eVA/view">working paper</a> earlier this month that collects some of the existing work-from-home research, pulling both from their own work and from other papers. One interesting finding is that although fully remote work has been correlated with a drop in productivity, hybrid work (which occurs widely in white-collar fields such as tech and business services) was not linked to any productivity loss—and could actually <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://siepr.stanford.edu/publications/working-paper/evolution-working-home">help with recruitment and retention</a> .<br><br> Workers gained freedom over their working conditions in the past few years. Now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/20/business/return-to-office-remote-work.html">many bosses</a> are trying to wrest that power back. And workers and managers don&#39;t always see eye to eye about the stakes of returning to work. Bloom and his colleagues asked managers and employees about how working from home affected productivity. Workers, on the whole, said they were 7.4 percent more productive on average while working from home; bosses said that they thought their employees were 3.5 percent less productive. Managers tend to most appreciate what they can see in front of them, Bloom told me over email: “It&#39;s like those restaurants where the kitchen is open and on display—it feels more like you are having a fantastic culinary experience, but it&#39;s really just a mirage.”<br><br> Companies&#39; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/31/business/work-home-return-office-amazon.html">rationales</a> for calling people back to work can seem mushy, beyond that it simply seems like being together would be better (or, in some cases, that employers want to fulfill expensive real-estate obligations). One argument for working in person is the idea that younger workers can learn from, and be mentored by, more experienced colleagues in the workplace. Bloom told me that senior managers over the age of 50 provide about 50 percent of the mentoring minutes when working from home as they do while in the office. “A lot of mentoring is casual, relaxed conversations and, yes, it&#39;s spontaneous—taking somebody aside and giving some quick advice,” he said. A Pew Research Center survey from March found that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/03/30/about-a-third-of-us-workers-who-can-work-from-home-do-so-all-the-time/">36 percent of teleworkers</a> said remote work hurt their opportunities to be mentored. Positive remote mentoring can happen (I found a formal mentorship program conducted mostly over Zoom very useful). Bloom said that although in theory—and with the right software—these types of relationships can blossom, “practically this does not happen as much online.”<br><br> Bloom&#39;s point (and my reaction to it) reinforces how personal experience can color perspectives on this issue: In my case, I both relish time away from home and believe in the potential of remote mentor relationships. But how those dimensions of work fit into our lives can vary widely. Change any inputs—personal commute time, age, nature of work, child-care responsibilities, goals—and the resulting approach may be unrecognizable.<br><br> <b>Related</b> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/us-remote-work-impact-fertility-rate-babies/673301/">The surprising effects of remote work</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/good-management-mentorship-remote-world/621219/">How to mentor young workers in a remote world</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>Russia is halting the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/17/world/europe/ukraine-russia-grain-deal.html">Black Sea Grain Initiative</a> , which ensured that Ukraine could export its grain by sea despite a wartime blockade and helped stabilize global food prices.</li><li> Senator Joe Manchin&#39;s decision to headline an event with the No Labels organization is <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-senator-manchin-speech-stokes-speculation-white-house-run-2023-07-17/">fueling speculation</a> over a potential third-party presidential run.</li><li> Firefighters are <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/16/us/california-wildfires-extreme-heat/index.html">battling several wildfires</a> in Southern California that ignited this weekend amid excessive heat warnings.</li><b>晚读</b><br><br>Do Yourself a Favor and Go Find a &#39;Third Place&#39;<br><br> <em>By Allie Conti</em><br><br><p> On a Sunday last year, I was walking through a suburban neighborhood in Pennsylvania, heading home from an early-afternoon meditation class. One of the nondescript stucco houses had a curious sticker on its mailbox reading mac&#39;s club. I checked Google Maps to see if I was standing next to a cleverly disguised business—what might pretentiously be referred to in a city as a speakeasy—but nothing popped up, so I peeked inside the house. That&#39;s where I spotted a pool table and a middle-aged guy sitting at the end of a long, mahogany bar, drinking a Bloody Mary by himself. Apparently I&#39;d stumbled upon a social club meant for residents of the neighborhood. Though at first the bartender was incredulous that I&#39;d just walked in, he soon rewarded my sense of adventure with a Guinness on the house. The Eagles weren&#39;t playing in the NFL that day, and he was grateful for the additional company. We talked about the upcoming deer season, and upon learning that I was a new hunter, the two guys showed me a rifle that was kept in another room. ……</p><p> Besides giving me the feeling that I&#39;d flexed a muscle that had atrophied, the interaction was special to me because I&#39;d found a classic “third place” in the suburbs, where I least expected it. The term, which was coined by the sociologist Ray Oldenburg in the 1980s, essentially refers to a physical location other than work or home where there&#39;s little to no financial barrier to entry and where conversation is the primary activity.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/04/third-places-meet-new-people-pandemic/629468/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/">Elizabeth Bruenig: Alabama wants to kill Jimi Barber.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/">The most shocking aspect of RFK Jr.&#39;s anti-Semitism</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/">Delivery apps just did the impossible.</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/mozart-in-motion-his-work-and-his-world-in-pieces-patrick-mackie/9780374606206?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Mozart in Motion</i></a> , by the British poet Patrick Mackie, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/mozart-in-motion-book-review-music/674726/">explores the secret to Mozart&#39;s lasting appeal</a> .<br><br><b>手表。</b> Beneath the hijinks and lewdness, the show <i>Dave</i> (streaming on Hulu) constructs <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/">an unlikely model</a> for male friendship.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br> <strong>PS</strong><br><br> I like to bake, and find doing so relaxing. But in the summer, when my apartment is hot, I turn to treats that don&#39;t require baking. (In case it hasn&#39;t become clear: I do not enjoy the sensation of being overheated.) One very easy and fun one I have returned to is these <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018460-chocolate-peanut-butter-cups">chocolate-peanut-butter cups</a> , courtesy of Samantha Seneviratne. I don&#39;t have a double boiler or a microwave, so I boil water in a saucepan and melt chocolate chips in a metal bowl on top of it. And I like cashew butter, so I use that instead of peanut butter. The effort-to-reward ratio is high: These take just a few minutes of active work and render delightful little treats.<br><br> — Lora<br><br> <i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Businessmen Broke Hollywood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> And now they don&#39;t want to pay their employees. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0uua5U8CtPMn05n96loBLb7ojPs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/hollywood_strike/original.jpg" alt="A photo of Hollywood actors on strike." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> David Butow / Redux</figcaption></figure> The Hollywood machine—from script writing, to shooting and production, to late-night talk-show PR—has officially ground to a halt.<br><br> On Thursday, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">the actors went on strike. The 160,000 members</a> of SAG-AFTRA, led by Fran Drescher, the fearless sitcom nanny, stopped working after talks with the studios collapsed. They join the ranks of the Writers Guild of America, whose members (myself included) have been on strike since May.<br><br> Our two unions have not been on strike together since 1960. The writers&#39; pickets at shooting locations had already shut down an estimated 80 percent of productions. Now SAG&#39;s strike rules dictate that actors not only can&#39;t shoot or do voice-over work for productions; they also cannot attend red carpets or promote any Motion Picture Association projects—something that was already a challenge, given that the writers&#39; strike had shut down the nighttime talk shows that were such a staple of the press circuit.<br><br> Much like the writers, actors are looking for increases in their residual pay—compensation that&#39;s akin to royalty checks—once-reliable income that has all but vanished in the pivot to streaming. Actors are also seeking protections against artificial intelligence using their voice and image.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">Xochitl Gonzalez: &#39;The whole thing starts with us&#39;</a><br><br> Bob Iger, Disney&#39;s CEO, called these expectations “just not realistic.” He accused the strikers of “adding to a set of challenges that this business is already facing that is quite frankly very disruptive and dangerous.”<br><br> This was a bit rich, coming days after a studio executive told <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/writers-strike-hollywood-studios-deal-fight-wga-actors-1235434335/"><i>Deadline</i></a> that their strategy was “to allow things to drag on until union members start losing their apartments and losing their houses.”<br><br> Eviction is a pretty cruel labor-negotiation strategy.<br><br> Hollywood&#39;s CEOs <i>are</i> suffering. Not primarily from labor disputes or industry disruption or public-relations issues, but from vincible ignorance, which seems to be endemic in C-suites of all industries. Under pressure to deliver to Wall Street, too many CEOs have lost the plot of their own movie. They are not running companies to profitably deliver a good product, such as a book or a cup of coffee or, in this case, a movie or TV show. They are running companies to deliver good profit. The quality of their product has ceased to matter.<br><br> If you doubt this, consider that when Emmy nominations were announced last week, the lions&#39; share went to HBO Max, a prestige platform that has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.insiderintelligence.com/content/charting-new-course-adapting-advertising-landscape-after-hbo-max-discovery-merger">ceased to exist by that name</a> , because Warner Bros. Discovery took the streaming arm of the legacy brand and folded it into a messy app crowded with low-budget reality programs. We are in the upside-down.<br><br> Writers and actors have been caught up in the pivot to streaming, the mad logic of which has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/writers-guild-contract-negotiation-mini-room-1235568173/">upended long-standing working practices</a> , slowly begun to replace human instinct with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/28/18637135/hollywood-ai-film-decision-script-analysis-data-machine-learning">artificial intelligence</a> , and obliterated workers&#39; income streams.<br><br> The actor Mark Proksch, for example, made more money off residuals from one season of guest appearances on <i>The Office</i> ,<i> </i>under the old system, than he has in five seasons of starring in <i>What We Do in the Shadows</i> , under the new system <i>.</i><br><br> Now, just as Hollywood workers are arguing that we need to adjust our compensation models to fit the streaming era, the studios are telling us that we cannot be fairly paid, because the streaming model is broken. And we&#39;re being told this by the very studio executives—many of them <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/ceo-pay-wga-writers-strike-1235351572/">multimillionaires</a> —who broke it.<br><br> This is another aspect of C-suite ignorance: Bonkers executive compensation has utterly detached leaders from the lives of the people they employ. The fact that David Zaslav, the CEO of Warner Bros. and Discovery, earned $247 million in 2021 makes it very hard to swallow his refusal to budge on issues that are costing middle-class actors thousands of dollars a year in lost income.<br><br> You can argue all you like about whether anyone should ever earn this much, but these are leaders who have made some disastrous business decisions.<br><br> The pivot to streaming was extremely profitable for the brief moment when everyone was trapped at home during a pandemic. People couldn&#39;t spend money on concerts or eating out or traveling, so they felt comfortable spending an abnormal amount on streaming services.<br><br> Hollywood CEOs saw the success of Netflix and raced to copy a model without knowing whether it was sustainable, a model that relied on the constant production of new (and costly) entertainment content created by unionized talent. They were wrong about the business, but they were even more wrong to presume that labor would comply. The actors and writers didn&#39;t make this pivot; why should they pay the price?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">Read: Why you should pay attention to the Hollywood writers&#39; strike</a><br><br> If the pivot to streaming was such a mistake that these businesses truly are going under—a case that&#39;s hard to make, given the size of these executives&#39; compensation packages—we will have to suffer too. But if we suffer during lean times, we should also share in the profits during fat ones. That is what the negotiations are about. The only way that executives will be able to right this ship is to return to making unmissable programming, and they won&#39;t be able to do that without us.<br><br> Absent good script writers, Hollywood executives have taken their lines from Marie Antoinette. But the revolutionaries are already outside, dismantling the palace. In London, the cast of <i>Oppenheimer</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oppenheimer-stars-walk-out-london-premiere-actors-strike-emily-blunt-matt-damon-florence-pugh-cillian-murphy/">walked out</a> of the film&#39;s premiere. Press tours for <i>Barbie</i> have been halted; even the stars&#39; pink-laden social-media accounts have gone dark. The Emmys will likely be <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/21/business/media/emmy-awards-writers-strike.html">postponed</a> . Comic-Con will be sans actors or writers. I am desperately hopeful that the studios will realize sooner rather than later that even if it hurts shareholders for a time, good entertainment, long-term, is always good business.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 19:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Most Shocking Aspect of RFK Jr.’s Anti-Semitism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> What&#39;s surprising isn&#39;t that Kennedy voiced an anti-Jewish conspiracy, but that it took this long. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rxpGHPhlsK812tEHTXc5twzmss8=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rfk_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="小罗伯特·RFK" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by The Atlantic. Source: Jamie McCarthy / Getty.</figcaption></figure> Last week, at a dinner event in Manhattan, the Democratic primary candidate Robert F. Kennedy Jr. shared his unvarnished thoughts about the nature of the coronavirus. “There&#39;s an argument that it is ethnically targeted,” he explained, in remarks <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/15/rfk-jr-says-covid-was-ethnically-targeted-to-spare-jews/">captured on video</a> . “COVID-19 is targeted to attack Caucasians and Black people. The people who are most immune are Ashkenazi Jews and Chinese.” To be sure, Kennedy added, “we don&#39;t know whether it was deliberately targeted or not.” In other words, Kennedy apparently believes it is an open question whether the pandemic was engineered by a shadowy cabal to spare Chinese and Jewish people.<br><br> At least 1 million people in China have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/china-million-covid-deaths-communist-party/673177/">died</a> from COVID-19; far from being immune to the virus, Jews in places like New York were often <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bklyner.com/editorial-stop-blaming-orthodox-jews-blame-trump-for-brooklyn-covid-spikes/">unfairly accused</a> of spreading it. As a Jew who had his own bout with the coronavirus, Kennedy&#39;s claims were news to me. But given the source, they also weren&#39;t a surprise. That&#39;s because Kennedy is a conspiracy theorist, and the arc of conspiracy is short and bends toward the Jews.<br><br> Here is just a small sampling of what Kennedy <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-jr-2024-election-anti-establishment-voters/674588/">believes</a> : that radiation from wireless internet <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D3OkKer7Ohw">causes</a> cancer; that chemicals in the water supply are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/13/politics/robert-kennedy-jr-chemicals-water-children-frogs/index.html">producing gender dysphoria</a> ; that the CIA killed both his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-interview-david-samuels#:~:text=he%20was%20also%20a%20CIA%20asset">father</a> and his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/3993563-robert-kennedy-jr-sees-overwhelming-evidence-cia-involved-in-jfk-assassination/">uncle</a> , President John F. Kennedy; that antidepressants <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/robert-kennedy-jr-elon-musk-american-revolution-twitter-spaces-conversation-2023-6">cause</a> today&#39;s mass shootings; that George W. Bush <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/politics/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-nut-job">stole</a> the 2004 presidential election; and that your phone&#39;s 5G connection is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2022/01/23/rfk-jr-compares-pandemic-mandates-to-nazi-germany/">part of a plot</a> “to harvest our data and control our behavior.”<br><br> Seen in the context of Kennedy&#39;s career, what&#39;s surprising is not his foray into anti-Semitism but that it took him this long to arrive here. As I&#39;ve <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">written before</a> :<br><br><p> Anti-Semitism is arguably the world&#39;s <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/texas-synagogue-anti-semitism-conspiracy-theory/621286/">oldest and most durable</a> conspiracy theory. It presents Jews as the string-pulling puppet masters behind the world&#39;s political, economic, and social problems. For those seeking simple solutions to life&#39;s complexities, this outlook offers a ready-made explanation—and enemy. Anyone seeking a single source for society&#39;s travails may start with run-of-the-mill conspiracy theories but will soon end up parroting anti-Jewish ideas.</p> Because anti-Semitism has produced centuries of material pinning humanity&#39;s problems on its Jews, a person convinced that an invisible hand is conducting world affairs will eventually discover that it belongs to an invisible Jew.<br><br> For this reason, it is impossible to circulate on the conspiratorial fringe and not encounter anti-Semitism. This is why Kennedy has constantly found himself in the company of those who believe and express anti-Jewish ideas. Last week, he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1678528085258301440">trumpeted</a> his meeting with the rapper Ice Cube, a fellow conspiracy theorist who has a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/ice-cube-criticized-anti-semitic-images-conspiracy-theories-9400472/">long history</a> of bizarre anti-Semitic tweets and song lyrics. In the past, Kennedy has also made <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LouisFarrakhan/status/614862836431392769">common</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4910041/user-clip-rfk-jr-told-louis-farrakhan-cdc-kill-black-boys">cause</a> with the hate preacher Louis Farrakhan, who regularly rails against alleged Jewish control of media and government.<br><br> That Kennedy would ultimately echo the anti-Semitic assumptions of his conspiratorial cohort was inevitable. Indeed, he is far from the first traveler on the well-trodden path from conspiracism to outright anti-Semitism. In recent years, individuals as diverse as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/61897999d581bf0020f74c32/why-rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-just-championed-louis-farrakhan/">Marjorie Taylor Greene</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/why-its-become-harder-to-joke-about-anti-semitism/672120/">Kyrie Irving</a> , and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">Elon Musk</a> have graduated from garden-variety conspiracy theories to anti-Jewish arguments. Even the content of Kennedy&#39;s COVID-19 conjecture isn&#39;t original: Jews have been blamed for spreading plagues for centuries, most famously during Europe&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/the-black-death">Black Death</a> .<br><br> Over the weekend, Kennedy furiously tweeted denials and clarifications, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1680227322509635595">insisting</a> that he meant only that COVID served “as a kind of proof of concept for ethnically targeted bioweapons,” not that “the ethnic effect was deliberately engineered,” though he&#39;d clearly raised that exact possibility in his original remarks.<br><br> Kennedy himself has no prior history of anti-Semitism, and has never evinced personal prejudice toward Jewish people. But his conspiratorial compass ensured that he would eventually arrive at this destination, because it points in only one direction.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:36:04 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Goodbye to the Prophets of Doom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The conventional wisdom about the global economy is that the rich have been getting richer and the poor have been getting poorer. What if that isn&#39;t true? <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AAP-a5AsFwsWVsmF4hkep4tT-TU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/inequality_2/original.jpg" alt="An illustration of a dollar bill creased to look like a staircase" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by The Atlantic. Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure> D <span class="smallcaps">uring the</span> Great Recession, public discourse about the economy underwent something of a Great Disappointment.<br><br> For much of the country&#39;s history, most Americans assumed that the future would bring them or their descendants greater affluence. Despite periodic economic crises, the overall story seemed to be one of progress for every stratum of the population. Those expectations were largely borne out: The standard of living enjoyed by working-class Americans for much of the mid-20th century, for example, was far superior to that enjoyed by affluent Americans a generation or two earlier.<br><br> But after the 2008 financial crisis, those assumptions were upended by a period of intense economic suffering coupled with a newfound interest among economists in the topic of inequality. Predictions of economic decline took over the conversation. America, a country long known for its inveterate optimism, came to dread the future—in which it now appeared that most people would have less and less.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/inflation-jobs-unemployment-recession/674593/">Adam Ozimek: The simple mistake that almost triggered a recession</a><br><br> Three arguments provided the intellectual foundation for the Great Disappointment. The first, influentially advanced by the MIT economist David Autor, was that the wages of most Americans were stagnating for the first time in living memory. Although the income of average Americans had roughly doubled once every generation for most of the previous century, wage growth for much of the population began to flatline in the 1980s. By 2010, it looked as though poorer Americans faced a future in which they could no longer expect any real improvement in their standard of living.<br><br> The second argument had to do with globalization&#39;s impact on the worldwide distribution of income. In a graph that came to be known as the “elephant curve,” the Serbian American economist Branko Milanović argued that the world&#39;s poorest people were experiencing only minor income growth; that the middle percentiles were benefiting mightily from globalization; that those in the upper-middle segment—which included many industrial workers and people in the service industry in rich countries, including America—had seen their incomes stagnate; and that the very richest were making out like bandits. Globalization, it seemed, was a mixed blessing, and a distinctly concerning one for the bottom half of wage earners in industrialized economies such as the United States.<br><br> The final, and most sweeping, argument was about the nature and causes of inequality. Even as much of the population was just holding its own in prosperity, the wealth and income of the richest Americans were rising rapidly. In his 2013 surprise best seller, <i>Capital in the Twenty-First Century</i> , the French economist Thomas Piketty proposed that this trend was likely to continue. Arguing that the returns on capital had long outstripped those of labor, Piketty seemed to suggest that only a calamitous event such as a major war—or a radical political transformation, which did not appear to be on the horizon—could help tame the trend toward ever-greater inequality.<br><br> The Great Disappointment continues to shape the way many Americans think about the current and future state of the economy. But as the pandemic and the rise of inflation have altered the world economy, the intellectual basis for the thesis has begun to wobble. The reasons for economic pessimism have started to look less convincing than they once were. Is it time to revise the core tenets of the Great Disappointment?<br><br> O <span class="smallcaps">ne of the mos</span> t prominent labor economists in the US, Autor has over the past decade provided much of the evidence regarding the stagnation of American workers&#39; incomes, especially for those without a college degree.<br><br> The US economy, Autor wrote in a highly influential <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hamiltonproject.org/publication/policy-proposal/the-polarization-of-job-opportunities-in-the-u-s-labor-market-implications-for-employment-and-earnings/">paper</a> in 2010, is bifurcating. Even as demand for high-skilled workers rose, demand for “middle-wage, middle-skill white-collar and blue-collar jobs” was contracting. America&#39;s economy, which had once provided plenty of middle-class jobs, was splitting into a highly affluent professional stratum and a large remainder that was becoming more immiserated. The overall outcome, according to Autor, was “falling real earnings for noncollege workers” and “a sharp rise in the inequality of wages.”<br><br> Autor&#39;s past work on the falling wages of a major segment of the American workforce makes it all the more notable that he now sounds far more optimistic. Because companies were desperately searching for workers at the tail-end of the pandemic, Autor argues in a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://economics.mit.edu/sites/default/files/2023-03/The%20Unexpected%20Compression%20-%20Competition%20at%20Work%20in%20the%20Low%20Wage%20Labor%20Market.pdf">working paper</a> published earlier this year, low-wage workers found themselves in a much better bargaining position. There has been a remarkable reversal in economic fortunes.<br><br> “Disproportionate wage growth at the bottom of the distribution reduced the college wage premium and reversed the rise in aggregate wage inequality since 1980 by approximately one quarter,” Autor writes. The big winners of recent economic trends are precisely those groups that had been left out in preceding decades: “The rise in wages was particularly strong among workers under 40 years of age and without a college degree.”<br><br> Even after accounting for inflation, Autor shows, the bottom quarter of American workers has seen a significant boost in income for the first time in years. The scholar who previously wrote about the “polarization” in the US workforce now concludes that the American economy is experiencing an “unexpected compression.” In other words, the wealth gap is narrowing with surprising speed.<br><br> A <span class="smallcaps">utor is not</span> the only leading economist who is calling into doubt the underpinnings of the Great Disappointment. According to Milanović, his “elephant curve” proved so influential in part because it confirmed fears many people had about the effects of globalization. His famous graph was, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.socialeurope.eu/global-income-inequality-time-to-revise-the-elephant">he now admits</a> , an “empirical confirmation of what many thought.” He is no longer so sure about that piece of conventional wisdom.<br><br> A few years ago, Milanović set out to update the original elephant curve, which was based on data from 1988 to 2008. The result came as a shock—a positive one. Once Milanović included data for another decade, to 2018, the curve changed shape. Instead of the characteristic “rise, fall, rise again” that had given the curve its viral name, its steadily falling gradient now seemed to paint a straightforward and much more optimistic picture. Over the four decades he now surveyed, the incomes of the poorest people in the world rose very fast, those of people toward the middle of the distribution fairly fast, and those of the richest rather sluggishly. Global economic conditions were improving for nearly everyone, and, contrary to conventional wisdom, it was the most needy, not the most affluent, who were reaping the greatest rewards.<br><br> In <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foreignaffairs.com/world/great-convergence-equality-branko-milanovic">a recent article for <i>Foreign Affairs</i></a> , Milanović goes even further. “We&#39;re frequently told,” he writes, that “we live in an age of inequality.” But when you look at the most recent global data, that turns out to be false: In fact, “the world is growing more equal than it has been for over 100 years.”<br><br> T <span class="smallcaps">o this day</span> , Piketty remains the patron saint of the Great Disappointment. No thinker is invoked more often to justify the theory. But even Piketty&#39;s pessimistic diagnosis, made a decade ago, has come to look much less dire.<br><br> In part, this is because Piketty&#39;s work has come in for criticism from other economists. According to one influential line of argument, Piketty mistook why returns on capital were higher than returns to labor in many industrialized countries in the decades after World War II. Absent concerted pressure to prevent this, Piketty had argued, the nature of capitalism would always favor billionaires and giant corporations over ordinary workers. But according to Matthew Rognlie, an economist at Northwestern University, Piketty&#39;s explanation for why<i> </i>inequality increased during that period was based on a misinterpretation of the data.<br><br> The outsize returns on capital during the latter half of the 20th century, Rognlie argues, were mainly due to the huge growth in house prices in metropolitan centers such as Paris and New York. If returns on capital were larger than returns to labor over this period, the reason was not a general economic trend but specific political factors, such as restrictive building codes. In addition, the main beneficiaries were not the billionaires and big corporations on which Piketty focused; rather, they were the kinds of upper-middle-class professionals who own the bulk of housing stock in major cities.<br><br> Economists continue to debate whether such criticisms hit the mark. But even as Piketty defended his work, he himself started to strike a more optimistic note about the long-term structure of the economy. In his 2022 book, <i>A Brief History of Equality</i> , he talks about the rise of inequality as an anomaly. “At least since the end of the eighteenth century there has been a historical movement towards equality,” he writes. “The world of the 2020s, no matter how unjust it may seem, is more egalitarian than that of 1950 or that of 1900, which were themselves in many respects more egalitarian than those of 1850 or 1780.”<br><br> Like Autor and Milanović, Piketty seems to have concluded that the thesis of the Great Disappointment was, in key respects, wrong.<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">t would be</span> premature to put worries about stagnating incomes or rising inequality to rest. The three former prophets of doom all emphasize the role that social and political factors play in shaping economic outcomes. As a result, they see recent wage growth for poorer Americans as caused in part by the expansionary economic policies that both Donald Trump and Joe Biden pursued in response to the pandemic.<br><br> Similarly, the huge gains that some of the poorest people in the world have made in recent decades derive in part from their governments&#39; efforts to use industrial policy to shape the impact of globalization on their countries. Whether, as Piketty has argued, the returns on capital will in the long run outstrip the returns to labor depends on political decisions about taxation and redistribution, about the strength of trade unions and the rules governing labor markets.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/labor-shortage-low-unemployment-inflation/674263/">Oren Cass: The labor-shortage myth</a><br><br> Recent good news about our economic prospects should not lead us to conclusions that could quickly turn out to be overexuberant. But we should also avoid perpetuating an instinctive pessimism that looks less and less warranted. Although pessimism may seem smart or shrewd, cynicism about our collective ability to build a better world only makes it harder to win support for the kind of economic policies we need to create that future.<br><br> Progressives sometimes seem to believe that they can mobilize people by making the future look scary. But when voters feel threatened, it is usually unscrupulous reactionaries who make unrealistic promises and scapegoat outsiders who benefit. Wage stagnation and rising inequality are still real dangers about which we must remain vigilant—but the fact that a better economic future has come to look a good deal more achievable should be cause for full-throated celebration.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Curious Personality Changes of Older Age]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> When people lose the ability to control their circumstances, their selves sometimes evolve instead. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/3HPxuP0gPOdamc0npNCyYsm2g2E=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/age_personality/original.jpg" alt="A group of older women chatting in a retro-looking laundry shop" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Martin Parr / Magnum</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br> Y <span class="smallcaps">ou&#39;ve probably heard</span> the saying “You can&#39;t teach an old dog new tricks.” An awful phrase, I know, but it speaks to a common belief about older adulthood: that it&#39;s a time of stagnation. A time when we&#39;ve become so set in our ways that, whether we&#39;re proud of them or not, we&#39;re not likely to budge.<br><br> Psychologists used to follow the same line of thinking: After young adulthood, people tend to settle into themselves, and personality, though not immutable, usually becomes stabler as people age. And that&#39;s true—until a certain point. More recent studies suggest that something unexpected happens to many people as they reach and pass their 60s: Their personality starts changing again.<br><br> This trend is probably observed in older populations in part because older adults are more likely to experience brain changes such as cognitive impairment and dementia. But some researchers don&#39;t believe the phenomenon is fully explained by those factors. People&#39;s personality can morph in response to their circumstances, helping them shift priorities, come to terms with loss, and acclimate to a changing life. These developments illuminate what personality really is: not a permanent state but an adaptive way of being. And on a societal level, personality changes might tell us something about the conditions that older adults face.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/older-adults-covid-health-quality-of-life/673507/">Read: Life is worse for older people now</a><br><br> P <span class="smallcaps">sychologists have</span> identified certain major, measurable personality traits called the “Big Five”: agreeableness, conscientiousness, extroversion, openness to experience, and neuroticism. And they can track how those traits increase or decrease in a group over time. To the surprise of many in the field, those kinds of studies are revealing that the strongest personality changes tend to happen <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/per.1966">before age 30—and after 60</a> . In that phase of later adulthood, people seem to decrease, on average, in openness to experience, conscientiousness, and extroversion—particularly a subcategory of extroversion called “social vitality.” And neuroticism tends to increase, especially <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26479363/">closer to the end</a> of one&#39;s life.<br><br> We can&#39;t say with certainty what factors are driving these shifts, but a few theories exist. One possibility is that personality is shaped by specific life events that tend to happen in older age: retirement, empty nesting, widowhood. But such milestones, it turns out, aren&#39;t very reliable sources of change; they affect some people deeply and others not at all. Any one event could mean many different things, depending on its context. Jenny Wagner, a psychologist at the University of Hamburg, in Germany, gave me some examples. Losing a partner could be a tremendous loss, but for some it could be a bit of a relief at the same time—say, for someone who&#39;s been caring for their ailing spouse for years. Retirement is the same: Where one person might be jumping from book club to vacation, another might be hobbled by lack of income, forced to move away from friends to a cheaper part of town.<br><br> At <em>any</em> age, life events can affect people differently. But in older adulthood particularly, researchers told me, people&#39;s daily realities vary wildly, so factors like health and social support are probably better predictors of personality change. “What you really want to know,” Wiebke Bleidorn, a personality psychologist at the University of Zurich, told me, “is <em>What are people&#39;s lives like?</em> ” If someone is no longer strong enough to go to dinner parties every week, they might grow less extroverted; if someone needs to be more careful of physical dangers like falling, it makes sense that they&#39;d grow more neurotic.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/03/how-to-change-your-personality-happiness/621306/">Read: I gave myself three months to change my personality</a><br><br> The idea that people might change who they are—really change, in a deep and even lasting way—in response to their circumstances might seem surprising. Many of us think of personality not as a set of dials we can modulate strategically but as something more akin to a hand of cards you&#39;ve been dealt. In truth, personality can likely be nudged by our environment and our relationships—our commitments to other people, and their expectations for us—at any age. But before older adulthood, people might commonly be less pressed to change themselves; they can usually change their habits and environments instead. Brent Roberts, a psychology professor at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, told me that “we construct our world to avoid” personality change. But if you can&#39;t take yourself to the grocery store, much less move to a different city, you might need to adapt. Once you lose control over elements of your life, Bleidorn said, you may alter your personality instead.<br><br> Granted, old-age personality changes don&#39;t always result from a sense of helplessness or an endlessly shrinking life. Research has shown that when people get older, they commonly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/gerontologist/article/61/8/1188/6412643">recalibrate their goals</a> ; though they might be doing less, they tend to prioritize what they find meaningful and really appreciate it. A decline in openness to experience, then, could reflect someone relishing their routine rather than seeking new thrills; a decline in extroversion could indicate that they&#39;re satisfied spending time with the people they already love. That may involve adjusting to what they can&#39;t control, but it doesn&#39;t necessarily mean they&#39;re reacting to a bad life—just a different one.<br><br> At the same time, not all of the changes that come with old age are inevitable. And if older adults had more support from their communities and society, perhaps they&#39;d be better able to command their circumstances—rather than having to compensate for factors slipping out of their grasp.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2020/01/old-people-older-elderly-middle-age/605590/">Read: When does someone become “old”?</a><br><br> Loneliness—which affects roughly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557972/">43 percent</a> of Americans 60 and over—can be a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ucsf.edu/news/2012/06/98644/loneliness-linked-serious-health-problems-and-death-among-elderly">particular challenge</a> for older people who, depending on their health and living situation, may have a hard time mitigating it. Older adults commonly experience friends dying, or have to move farther away from friends to enter care facilities or be closer to family; health issues can make socializing physically harder, especially for those who can&#39;t safely drive. And <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/older-adults-covid-health-quality-of-life/673507/">the pandemic</a> has pushed many older people further into seclusion than ever. But there are ways to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.2019.00203">work against these factors</a> : Programs to help with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eldercare.acl.gov/public/resources/factsheets/home_modifications.aspx">home modifications</a> could allow older adults to stay in their houses and neighborhoods for longer; affordable housing in areas with large senior populations could help older adults live in close proximity to one another; car services and more accessible public transit could transport them to social events. “To the extent that we can create communities for older individuals,” Roberts told me, “they would probably show a more healthy pattern of personality change.”<br><br> One study, for instance, found that older adults who felt they had more social support were more likely to grow in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4111302/">conscientiousness</a> over time. You can imagine similarly positive results might stem from older adults having access to the health care they need, or having the tools to navigate their daily lives safely and without total dependence on others. Dan Mroczek, a psychologist at Northwestern University, gave me a common example: Say someone has put off leaving their home for a care facility, and one day they find they&#39;re unable to climb their own stairs. Now they need to move out fast—but spots are filled in all of the most palatable places. He wouldn&#39;t be surprised, he told me, if someone quickly grew more neurotic in that situation.<br><br> There&#39;s a stereotype that older people are grumpy shut-ins—withering away inside while yelling at some kid to get off their lawn. That judgment is obviously sweeping and unfair, but perhaps it&#39;s also emerged, in part, from some real tendencies—tendencies that might be better understood as justified reactions to a harsh and inaccessible world. America&#39;s population is rapidly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/10/aging-america/503177/">growing older</a> , and life expectancy, except for a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/pressroom/nchs_press_releases/2022/20220831.htm">recent dip</a> , has been getting longer. By 2040, about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://acl.gov/news-and-events/news/2040-one-five-americans-will-be-over-age-65">one in five</a> Americans will be 65 or older; as recently as 2000, that number was one in eight. Perhaps we&#39;d do well to consider what older people&#39;s living conditions can push them to become.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 12 Jul 2023 13:48:39 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/old-age-personality-brain-changes-psychology/674668/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/old-age-personality-brain-changes-psychology/674668/</item></channel></rss>